\section*{ELECTRONIC MEDICAL RECORD SYSTEM}

Definition:
Electronic medical records about patient care that are kept on a compute rather than on paper, the tradition medium for patient his tories. Thos e records can include extensive information about patient's general health, current and past illness and medical conditions diagnostic results and treatment and medication prescribed. Often electronic medical records also include an application for pres cribing and ordering medication.

Medical records ensure that patients receive the best medical care possible and that they are kept safe during treatment. Traditional paper mean of medical record keeping can be burdens ome to maintain and track causing electronic medical records to come into safer. Knowing what electronic medical records are and how they work can help a medical clinic or hospital determine i.e. the implementation of an electronic system would be beneficial.

The medical industry uses electronic patient's records as a mean of establishing more convenient and efficient patient records health care offices and hospitals can integrate computers into their clinical practice.

Electronic patient records are clinical records that are stored electronically in a computer bas ed system according to open clinical patient records house various types of information about a patient record even have technological capabilities to track patient billing information and keep track of patient appointment.

An electronic medical record is any medical record that is kept in electronic format. They contain the same information as traditional paper medical records (e.g. patient name, condition, medicine prescribed) but the data is not written out longhand. Instead it is entered into some type of electronic device such as a computer or PDA the data can be retrieved by these devices later when needed.

\section*{CREATION}

Electronic medical records most commonly are created on computers. The computer is set up with some type of records software and a technician enters data into the fields in the software to save it into the system. Most types of medical record software have the ability to search for particular data such as patientsâ€™ last name or insurance number. This will help to retrieve data very quickly. EMR also can be created by sophis ticated medical devices such as machines e.g. that monitor the heart it sends data to a server during a stress test. Due to advances in the technology, they even can be created through application on cellular phones.

\section*{AUTHENTICATION}

As with tradition medical records, technicians still need to verify that the information contained in electronic medical records is accurate. EMR must be unaltered and be authenticated in order for them to be accepted for use.

\section*{BENEFITS}

EMR greatly reduces the amount of space needed for record storage. They also decrease the amount of time that a must be spent physically retrieving files. They can be transmitted over a long distances in a matter of seconds, can be more legible than handwritten records. Lastly electronic records speed up billing and inquiry processes which means the hospital is able to serve more people and provide better services.

EMR alleviate some administrative burden for medical officers because they eliminate the need for documents to be billed and filed. This saves medical professionals time, which can be better spent with patients.

\section*{CONCERNS}

EMR are prone to data entry errors. They also are sensitive to data corruption if an electronic record is lost and there is no paper record, there may be no way to retrieve the data. EMR keeping als o means that those who create and use the records must be comfortable with the related technology. Cost may rise for the hospital due to their training requirements, the purchas e of necess ary equipments and technology support.

\section*{FEATURES}

Medical professionals can enter new patients into their electronic records system easily, as well as change and update pre-existing records. Records can be deleted when patients are no longer a part of that doctor's office, they can be faked to specialty providers for medical collaboration and copies can be printed for patients to take home.

\section*{ADVANTAGES OF EMR}
1. The data tends to be more accurate. Electronic records eliminates the possibility of mistakes as a result of misleading a doctors hand writing
2. They are easily accessible to all care providers and more than one care providers at $s$ time
3. They are easy to store and take up less space than paper records
4. They are easily portable form one doctor's office to another
5. Their use can lead to cost saving since keeping electronic records is more efficient than retaining paper records.

\section*{DISADVANTAGES}
1. The possibility of incompatibility of computer system among various health care providers can lead to difficulty in sharing the data
2. Privacy and security cab be an is sue, if someone hacks into the system, thous ands of patients records can be compromised.
3. When a computer crashes makes records inaccessible
4. The cost of implementing an electronic records system can be expensive

\section*{OBSTACLES}

Cost remains a major deterrent to the implementation of electronic medical records, especially in small practices. The initial outlay for these systems can cost hundreds of thous ands of dollars, something many physicians are not willing to spend. Doctor's reluctance to accept the new systems has also slowed their adoption in the United States, according to a journal of American Medical Association

