\section*{a) Checking for completeness.}
-The methods by which patient names may reach the waiting list have already been described. It's possible however that a particular name may be missed, the doctor may think he ask the nurse or the receptionist to make a card but may not have done so.
- The hospital may send a letter for the GP (Dr.) saying that an admission is planned but unless the Dr. has a very clear idea as to when the patient is going to be admitted he is likely to follow this information up. The patient will wait believing that his name is on the waiting list and he will be admitted in due course. A failure to enter the patient name on the waiting list, therefore would lead to grave delay and prejudice the patient chances of recovery.

\section*{b) Checking for Accuracy}
-Where a hospital has a large waiting list of more than 1000 waiting for admission, some of these patients will wait for a long time.
-It is important to be certain that the patients at the list are still in need of treatment and have not moved from the area or had the operation carried out a another hospital.
-It is necessary in order to make this check, to write periodically to all patients who have been on the list for more than 6 months or year. The letter must be carefully worded explaining that the list is being checked and asking if the patient still needs to come in to the hospital. The patient should also be asked if he feels that for any reason admission is no longer necessary. A business reply or stamped envelope should be included with the enquiry. Most patients will reply saying that they still wish to come in some will have had treatment els ewhere, while some say they no longer wish to come in. The replies of the letters in two categories must be referred to the consultant as he will wish to write to the patient. GPs before taking the patient names of the list. These
