Appointment system is a system is a systematic way of giving a specific date, time and venue of the clinic to an individual patient/ client.

\section*{CONCEPTS OF SCHEDULING}
1. Patients should be distributed evenly to various clinics depending on the number that the consultants will be able to see.
2. The staff meaning the clinics should ensure that they are in time so that the patients are not kept waiting for long before they are seen
3. Overloading of clinics should be avoided
4. There should be a laid down policy on how to schedule current cases
5. Staff working in the appointment area should be familiar with the layout of the hospital so that they can give proper direction to the patients/ clients.

\section*{PURPOSE OF SCHEDULING AND FOLLOWUP}
a) To reduce patients' waiting time
b) To provide an even spread of work over the whole clinic session. An appointment provides for even spread of work among the medical staff running the clinic.
c) To allow the hospital to prepare each and every patient in advance so that delay for regis tration at the time of the clinic is or can be reduced.
d) To provide special clinic arrangements, for example recording of social his tory, weighing of patients, removal of plaster, pathological and radiological examinations.
e) To allow for distance and known transport difficulties. Allowance should be made by health record staff for such factors as the distance a patient has to travel, train and arrival and departure times, rural transport difficulties, availability of local ambulance to the health care facility. All these can cons is tently ease burden of attending the hospital.
f) To provide for teaching arrangements. A consultant may wish to select an interesting case to present to the medical students. This is simplified if an appointment system is well organized in the health institution.

\section*{TYPES OF APPOINTMENT SYSTEMS}

There are 3 types
A. CENTRALIZED
B. DECENTRALIZED
C. COMBINED

\section*{A. CENTRALIZED}

This means that all appointments for the various clinics are made in one central place. (Same work being done in one area)

\section*{ADVANTAGES}
i. The master index card will be near the area for quick reference
ii. Control of staff, stationery and equipment by the health records \& Information Officer is easy.
iii. Each of the appointment clerks becomes familiar with the working systems of the various consultants.
iv. All inquiries concerning appointments are referred to one place.
v. Urgent cases are channeled quickly to the respective clinics.
vi. When one clerk is sick or goes on leave, the other clerk continuous with the work since they are all familiar with the work.

\section*{B. DECENTRALIZED}

This is an appointment system which is carried on different clinics.

\section*{ADVANTAGES}
i. The clerk dealing with the appointments becomes familiar with the patients and knows them by name.
ii. The consultant of the clinic in charge of the clinic will know the number of patients on his list without having to walk or ring the central area.

\section*{DISADVANTAGES}
i. The master index is far from the appointment area.
ii. Control of available resources is difficult
iii. When the clerk who mans the clinic becomes sick or is on leave, the work come to a stand still
iv. Enquiries concerning appointments are directed to different places

\section*{C. COMBINED}

Some of the hospital has the two systems combined. Return appointments being made in the various clinics and new bookings being done in the central area. Therefore it is the duty of health records/information officer to look at these systems critically to decide on which suits his/her hospital or health institution.

\section*{SOURCES OF REQUEST FOR APPOINTMENTS}
a) Patients telephoning personally to make appointments
b) Physicians on private practice wanting to book appointments for their patients through telephone or writing.
c) Letters from health institution given to patients to come and book their own appointments
d) Patients already discharged from the hospital making return appointment
e) Patients referred from other clinics or from one clinic to another.

